<P>
<b><center>Basic Operations </center></b><font size="--">


<P>Computer Logic or Circuit Logic can be used in a variety of ways. 
eg. In helping to solve practical work in a control engineering problem.


<P>Signals can be:


<ul><LI>analogue
<Br><LI>digital
<Br><LI>binary (0 or 1)</UL>


<P>A large proportion of the control systems using binary signals can be described as switching algebra eg. a feed table of a milling machine may only be operating if :-


<UL>
<LI>mill machine is running</LI>
<LI>coolant is being pumped</LI>
<LI>protective grate closed</LI>
<LI>feed motor is on</LI></UL>
<P>

<B>Basic Operations</B>
<P>The processing potential of binary signals can be described using the three basic operations:-</P>
<b>
<UL> <LI>AND
<LI>OR
<LI>NOT (negation)
</UL></b>

These basic operations are used to solve basic combinatorial control problems.
<P>
<B><P>AND Logic Operator</P></B>
<P>Operationally, the output signal is 1 only when all input signals are 1.</P>

